	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Aug 23rd 3:49 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.90]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Until I am able to win the lottery or find a way to play while I work, I will have to accept the fact that I will never see the planes or even the high 20's for that matter.&nbsp;&nbsp;With my limited time though, I have had the chance to experiment with some of the many classes and have found that IMO the shaman provides the casual player a great amount of flexibility to either solo play or group if time permits.  Most of my shaman life has been spent as a barbarian, however, I have toyed with an ogre as well.  I am almost to the fourth circle of spells so my views will apply to those who are very young or are considering the shaman profession (especially those of the barbarian persuasion) so for those of higher levels and greater experience please be kind.  <br><br>The beginning 3-4 levels are not much unlike any other.  Familiarize yourself with you starting spells, get the best weapon you can at this time (preferably both 1 and 2 handed blunt to practice with), and get to know everfrost very well. There are several quests however that are very doable at this level that are also very rewarding.  There numerous sites dedicated to outlining these so I won't begin to go into them, but I would suggest saving the spider fungus, good polar bear skins, and goblin neckaces that you find and figure out what to do with them.  Since there also is an overabundance of skeletons in everfrost, I would recommend saving and not selling those bone chips.  These can be sold to passing necromancers you may encounter and can sometimes fetch a very nice price (sold 3 stacks for 30pp not long ago).<br><br>Once you reach 5th level and have your second circle of spells you can begin to invade the gnoll stronghold known as Blackburrow.  Initially you may need a partner and hunt around the entrance.  The gnolls here carry both coin and loot that can make for decent income.  Some I have talked to prefer to pass right on thru BB and on to Qeynos Hills or other areas.  These can be very rewarding as well in experience, loot, as well as quests.  It's really up to what you want to do.  As for me, I had a full suit of chain mail armor by level 9, have added several pieces of banded by level 13, have all spells available and still have nearly 100pp in the bank. <br><br>By level 10 you can start grouping in BB for those gnoll elites, or head to the plains for mammoth calfs, snow leopards and snow orc troopers.  You will find great experience and the mammy's and troopers can drop some vauluable loot.  At 10-13 you can also begin hunting the wisps for their lightstones to be sold or used for specific quests.  Remember to have a magical weapon or you may find yourself retrieving your corpse a lot.  If you can find the rabid wolves and bears in Qeynos hills I would highly recommend killing them whenever possible.  I have heard there is a priestess in Qeynos who greatly values their skins.<br><br>The shamans spells are your most important asset at every point.  Everything from buffs, DOT's, debuffs, healing and DD allow you to provide yourself and those you may group with a great number of services.  With good armor at these levels you can tank fairly effectively and when added to the DOT's you can stack by level 9 this can be deadly for many opponents.  SOW at level 9 is definately a plus since druids do not have this ability until level 14.  You can supplement your income by providing this service if you feel the need to charge outright or accept donations. (I have received 25pp for a sow, granted it was all in gp...hehe...some high powered wizard's pocket lint)  Don't forget the debuff's....drowsy et al can greatly reduce the damage you take while meleeing a mob as well as give you more time to cast between hits.<br><br>I hope that this will provide a helpful start to those who are like me and don't have more than a few hours a week to dedicate to this dreaded addiction.  I also have had some great experiences travelling to far off lands.  The run accross Antonica at level 8 with my warrior was quite the nail biter.  Have fun, make friends and please be good to those around you....they will probably be 10 levels above you the next time you are able to play.  <br><br>I have recently reached level 14 and have discovered the world of real DD spells (Spirit Strike 75pts/cast), improved debuffs, root, and some upgraded shielding.  Spirit of Snake helps with the vendors and levitating newbies has become a fun pastime when plaqued by requests for buffs. (Of course I'm happy to buff them but shouldn't I get some enjoyment out of it).  Will probably be a while before 19 and the next circle of spells but have found that elite gnolls make for good hunting/experience/loot/coin.  Am thinking about travelling to Oasis or Highpass...will send a postcard if I do.  Best wishes to all and safe travels.  <br><br>&nbsp;<br>Xegony<br>Sarlaana, Shaman of the 15th season<br>Mopar, Warrior of the 16th season</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
